{"cursor":"4042","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'French Flag Model' is a conceptual definition of a morphogen, described by\nLewis Wolpert in the 1960s. A morphogen is rigorously\ndefined as a signaling molecule that acts directly on cells (not through serial\ninduction) to produce specific cellular responses dependent on morphogen\nconcentration. During early development, morphogen gradients generate different\ncell types in distinct spatial order.\n\nIn the French flag model, the French flag is used to represent the effect of a\nmorphogen on cell differentiation: a morphogen affects cell states based on\nconcentration, these states are represented by the different colors of the\nFrench flag: high concentrations activate a \"blue\" gene, lower concentrations\nactivate a \"white\" gene, with \"red\" serving as the default state in cells below\nthe necessary concentration threshold.\n\nThe French Flag model was championed by the leading Drosophila biologist, Peter\nLawrence. Christiane NÃ¼sslein-Volhard identified the first morphogen, Bicoid,\none of the transcription factors present in a gradient in the Drosophila\nsyncytial embryo. Two labs, that of Gary Struhl and that of Stephen Cohen, then\ndemonstrated that a secreted signaling protein, Decapentaplegic (the Drosophila\nhomologue of Transforming Growth Factor Beta), acted as a morphogen during later\nstages of Drosophila development. substance governing the pattern of tissue\ndevelopment and, in particular, the positions of the various specialized cell\ntypes within a tissue. It spreads from a localized source and forms a\nconcentration gradient across a developing tissue.\n\nWell-known morphogens include: Decapentaplegic / Transforming growth factor\nbeta, Hedgehog / Sonic Hedgehog, Wingless / Wnt, Epidermal growth factor, and\nFibroblast growth factor.\n\nSome of the earliest and best-studied morphogens are transcription factors that\ndiffuse within early [[Drosophila melanogaster]] (fruit fly) embryos. However,\nmost morphogens are secreted proteins that signal between cells.\n\nMorphogens are defined conceptually, not chemically, so simple chemicals such as\nretinoic acid may also act as morphogens.\n","linknr":114,"url":"French_flag_model","recorded":1364132101,"links":["/w/index.php?title=French_flag_model&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=French_flag_model&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Concs.gif","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/Concs.gif","/wiki/File:Concs.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Lewis_Wolpert","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Morphogen","/w/index.php?title=Serial_induction&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Flag_of_France","/wiki/Peter_Lawrence_(biologist)","/wiki/Christiane_N%C3%BCsslein-Volhard","/wiki/Drosophila_embryogenesis","/w/index.php?title=Gary_Struhl&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Stephen_Cohen_(biologist)&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Concentration_gradient","/wiki/Decapentaplegic","/wiki/Transforming_growth_factor_beta","/wiki/Hedgehog_(cell_signaling)","/wiki/Sonic_hedgehog","/wiki/Wnt_signaling_pathway","/wiki/Wnt_signaling